\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Monitoring Scope and Configuration Ownership
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department shall maintain real-time monitoring coverage across all IT services,
 infrastructure,
 endpoints,
 and applications within the scope defined in Section 2.
 In-scope data collection includes availability and ping checks,
 performance metrics,
 flow data,
 syslog and event logs,
 and SNMP polling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Network Administrator owns monitoring configurations for all network equipment within scope.
 The Systems Administrator owns the monitoring collection infrastructure and all server-side monitoring configurations.
 The Assistant IT Director is accountable for ensuring that both configuration sets are current,
 functional,
 and producing data sufficient to support event classification under this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Tool configurations,
 procedures,
 and monitoring runbooks shall be maintained in the Knowledge Base under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Event Taxonomy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All events generated by the monitoring function shall be classified under the following four-tier taxonomy,
 regardless of monitoring stream.
 A single taxonomy governs all in-scope monitoring data types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Informational
\series default
 —
 System behavior is within normal parameters.
 No action is required.
 Events at this tier shall be logged for baseline and trending purposes.
 No work order is generated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Warning
\series default
 —
 System behavior is approaching a defined threshold.
 No action is required.
 Events at this tier shall be logged.
 The Assistant IT Director shall maintain awareness of Warning-tier events as part of the threshold review obligations established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 Section 6.3.
 No work order is generated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Alert
\series default
 —
 A defined threshold has been breached and action is required.
 A work order shall be generated in Redmine at Urgent or High severity,
 determined by the scope of impact at the time of the event.
 Alert-tier events initiate the 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 incident intake process and are subject to all intake,
 triage,
 and response obligations defined there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Major
\series default
 —
 Service impact is confirmed or imminent.
 A work order shall be generated in Redmine at Critical severity.
 The IT Director shall be notified immediately.
 Major-tier events initiate the 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 incident intake process and are subject to all intake,
